WEBVTT

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:09.110
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:09.110 --> 00:00:12.520
In this video what we'd like
to do is to solve a certain

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:13.500
differential equation.

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:15.660
And I'm not even giving
you initial condition.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:20.030
So we just want to find a y,
such that x times dy dx is

00:00:20.030 --> 00:00:23.480
equal to x squared plus x
times y squared plus 1.

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:24.850
So I'll give you a minute
to think about it and

00:00:24.850 --> 00:00:26.100
then I'll be back.

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:35.450
Welcome back.

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:38.610
I'm going to use the technique
of separation of variables to

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:40.620
solve this differential
equation problem.

00:00:40.620 --> 00:00:42.470
Hopefully you thought about
doing that as well.

00:00:42.470 --> 00:00:44.250
Because it's really
set up nicely for

00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:45.930
separation of variables.

00:00:45.930 --> 00:00:51.460
So let me let me first get all
of the values, or terms that

00:00:51.460 --> 00:00:53.450
involve y on the
left-hand side.

00:00:53.450 --> 00:00:56.700
And then I'm going to move the
dx to the right-hand side and

00:00:56.700 --> 00:01:00.390
get all the terms that involve
x to the right-hand side.

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:04.510
So I'm going to write dy
divided by y squared

00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:08.100
plus 1 is equal to--

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:11.800
so I'm going to multiply through
by dx divided by x.

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:16.200
So I'm going to get x squared
plus x over x dx.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:19.360
Now if x is 0, I have a little
problem but we're going to

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:20.540
ignore that for the moment.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:27.420
So I can rewrite this
as x plus 1 dx.

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:31.150
And now I'm totally set up
with my next step in

00:01:31.150 --> 00:01:34.340
separation of variables and so
I can integrate both sides.

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:36.950
So let's see what happens
when I integrate

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:37.710
the left-hand side.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:40.370
OK?

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:44.020
What is an antiderivative to
1 over y squared plus 1?

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:47.580
Well that's arctangent, that's
arctangent of y.

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:50.760
So the derivative of arctangent
of y is 1 over y

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:51.640
squared plus 1.

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:54.110
And so on the left-hand
side I get arctan y.

00:02:01.790 --> 00:02:06.340
If you wrote tangent to the
minus 1 y, that's the same

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.570
thing, the inverse tangent of
y, that's the same thing.

00:02:09.570 --> 00:02:11.570
And on the right-hand
side what do I get?

00:02:11.570 --> 00:02:15.360
Well this is a nice easy
thing to integrate.

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:17.960
When I integrate x, I get
x squared over 2.

00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:19.320
And here I just get an x.

00:02:19.320 --> 00:02:22.610
And then I should add
in my constants.

00:02:22.610 --> 00:02:27.780
So x squared over 2 plus
x plus a constant.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:31.390
So this is, so far I'm
doing everything OK.

00:02:31.390 --> 00:02:33.600
Now I need to figure out
how to isolate the y.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:36.870
Well arctan y is the inverse
of the tangent function.

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:39.930
So if I want to isolate y I have
to take the tangent of

00:02:39.930 --> 00:02:40.950
both sides.

00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:44.200
So when I take tangent of
arctangent of y I just get y.

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:49.660
Then over your I get tangent
of x squared over 2 plus x

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:52.140
plus C.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:54.530
And now because I didn't give
you any initial conditions, we

00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:57.590
can't say anything about C. But
if I gave you some initial

00:02:57.590 --> 00:03:00.620
conditions then we could
evaluate and solve for C. Now

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:03.030
how do I go about checking to
make sure that this works?

00:03:03.030 --> 00:03:05.330
Well, what I do is actually
take the derivative.

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:09.480
So you may want to take the
derivative of the right-hand

00:03:09.480 --> 00:03:11.410
side, take dy dx.

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:15.430
Evaluate what that is when you
have y equals tangent of x

00:03:15.430 --> 00:03:20.250
squared over 2 plus x plus C and
see if you in fact get the

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:22.220
relationship you're
supposed to get.

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:23.930
But I'll stop there.